prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The correlator is configured with two bands set to low-resolution continuum (4 GHz bandwidth). The other two base bands are configured to observe 13CO (3-2) with ~0.13 km/s resolution (234 MHz bandwidth - 213 km/s) and 12CO (J=3-2) ~0.5 km/s resolution (937 MHz bandwidth - 813 km/s). We plan to bin the 13 CO channels to 0.26 km/s to increase the signal-to-noise ratio, enhancing detectability of kinematic structures toward protostellar disks. The 12CO velocity resolution is sufficient to detect outflow emission from protostellar sources, which typically has emission from 0.5 klm/s out to +/- 20 km/s (or more). The full velocity extent of outflow emission will fit within the 813 km/s bandwidth.
We chose wide bandwidths for the 12CO and 13CO such that the line-free channels would also contribute to the continuum bandwidth. We expect that 80% of the 12CO band will be line-free and that 95% of the 13CO band will be line-free. Thus, the total useable continuum bandwidth is expected to be 4.725 GHz.

We have chosen 0.09" resolution because this corresponds to ~38 AU at the distance to the Orion molecular clouds. One of the primary science goals is to determine if there is a peak in multiplicity at ~75 AU scales, similar to what is found in the Perseus molecular cloud. This resolution is sufficient to resolve multiple systems at 75 AU scale, but also enough to see if multiplicity falls off toward even smaller separations (as also seen in Perseus). The largest angular scale is 1.5", the maximum achievable with the single high-resolution configuration. This will enable us to recover structures as large as 630 AU in diameter, this size is comparable to the diameter of a large protostellar disk. Most disks are expected to be smaller than 300 AU, thus we will be able to recover the full extent of dust continuum emission from the protostellar disks.

Our main focus in the proposal is the continuum sensitivity. Assuming a 30 K dust temperature and optically thin emission, our 5-sigma dust+gas mass sensitivity will be 0.000725 solar masses. For comparison, a typical T-Tauri disk mass (gas+dust) is 0.005 solar masses (gas+dust; Andrews et al. 2005), so we will be able to detect even very faint low-mass disks. For example, we would detect all the detected disks in the Andrews et al. (2005) sample. Thus, it will be feasible to detect even very low mass disks around stars of all evolutionary stages. Moreover, the disks and compact structures around the Class 0 and I protostars are expected to be larger than T-Tauri disk masses. For instance, the protostellar disk around L1527-IRS is only 0.007 solar masses and our survey would detected at the ~50 sigma level. Also, Tobin et al. (2015) presented a CARMA survey Perseus protostars with a 5-sigma mass sensitivity of 0.0029 solar masses (~1 mJy/beam). The proposed Orion survey goes to 4x greater depths than was possible for sources 2x closer with only ~50s on each source, whereasthe Perseus survey in Tobin et al. (2015) spent ~2 hours on source. The large dynamic range of masses probed is essential to detect not only those sources with massive inner envelopes and disks, but also lower mass sources in order to sample the full variety of disk/compact masses toward protostars.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The formation of disks and multiple systems is thought to begin during the early phases of the star formation process. However, sufficient numbers of young protostars (Class 0 and I phases) have not been observed at high enough resolution to determine when and where most multiples form and whether or not large disks are common. To make significant progress in these areas of star formation study, we propose an unbiased ALMA Band 7 survey of the 331 known protostars in the Orion A and B molecular clouds at 0.09" (38 AU) resolution. Orion is the only massive star forming region within 500 pc and the resolution and sensitivity of ALMA will enable us to characterize the separation distribution of multiple systems and size distribution of protostellar disks. CO and 13CO (J=3-2) lines will be observed simultaneously to determine the compact outflow directions and observe disk kinematics. This study will be the largest and most complete high-resolution submillimeter survey of protostars ever undertaken and will significantly improve our understanding of the formation mechanisms and prevalence of close multiples and disks during the early stages of star formation.
